SIMPLE: fact
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Fact
<hw>Fact</hw> <pr>(f⟦acr⟧kt)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>factum</ets>, fr. <ets>facere</ets> to make or do. Cf.
<er>Feat</er>, <er>Affair</er>, <er>Benefit</er>, <er>Defect</er>,
<er>Fashion</er>, and <er>-fy</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A doing,
making, or preparing.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A project for the <qex>fact</qex> and vending⟦br⟧
Of a new kind of fucus, paint for ladies.</q> <rj><qau>B.
Jonson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>An effect produced or achieved; anything done or
that comes to pass; an act; an event; a circumstance.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>What might instigate him to this devilish <qex>fact</qex>, I am
not able to conjecture.</q> <rj><qau>Evelyn.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He who most excels in <qex>fact</qex> of arms.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Reality; actuality; truth; <as>as, he, in
<ex>fact</ex>, excelled all the rest; the <ex>fact</ex> is, he was
beaten.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>The assertion or statement of a thing done or
existing; sometimes, even when false, improperly put, by a transfer of
meaning, for the thing done, or supposed to be done; a thing supposed or
asserted to be done; <as>as, history abounds with false
<ex>facts</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I do not grant the <qex>fact</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>De
Foe.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This reasoning is founded upon a <qex>fact</qex> which is not
true.</q> <rj><qau>Roger Long.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ The term <xex>fact</xex> has in jurisprudence peculiar
uses in contrast with <xex>law</xex>; as, attorney at <xex>law</xex>,
and attorney in <xex>fact</xex>; issue in <xex>law</xex>, and issue in
<xex>fact</xex>. There is also a grand distinction between
<xex>law</xex> and <xex>fact</xex> with reference to the province of the
judge and that of the jury, the latter generally determining the
<xex>fact</xex>, the former the <xex>law</xex>.</note>
<rj><au>Burrill</au> <au>Bouvier.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Accessary before the fact</b></col>, <it>or</it>
<col><b>Accessary after the fact</b></col></mcol>. <cd>See under
<er>Accessary</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Matter of fact</b></col>, <cd>an
actual occurrence; a verity; used adjectively: of or pertaining to
facts; prosaic; unimaginative; <as>as, a <ex>matter-of-fact</ex>
narration</as>.</cd></cs></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Act; deed; performance; event; incident;
occurrence; circumstance.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>fact-finding</ent>⟦br⟧
